What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset represents the loans made by a peer-to-peer lending based compny called Prosper . The dataset has 113937 records with 81 columns. There are a set of columns that describe the loan, for e.g. Terms, BorrowerAPR, LoanStatus. Then, there are attributes related to the credit-worthiness of the borrower, for e.g. ProsperScore, StatedMonthlyIncome, and Employmentstatus.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

There are two areas I want to explore

  1. What factors impact the APR that the borrower recieves
  2. What factors can help predict that a borrower will default

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Based on my understanding of the financual industry, I think following features can provide useful insight into my features of interest

  • Term
  • LoanStatus
  • BorrowerAPR
  • BorrowerRate
  • ProsperScore
  • Occupation
  • EmploymentStatus
  • StatedMonthlyIncome

  • LoanOriginalAmount

    I will begin with exploring these variables individually to understand how they are distributed across the population

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I looked at APR and default rate of customers. The most frequent APR offered on Prosper's platform is 0.36%, which could be a standard in the industry. The graph appears multi-modal with peaks at different data points: 0.1%, 0.2%, 0.3% and then the highest peak at 0.36%.

Around 15% of the customers on Prosper's platform have either defaulted or have been charged off. This seems to be quite high based on the US industry average (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer-to-peer_lending#:~:text=The%20interest%20rates%20range%20from,for%20the%20more%20risky%20borrowers.)

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distribution for StatedMonthlyIncome was highly right skewed due to a few customers with unusually high monthly income, highest being 145K. I suspect it could be because of incorrect data. To remove these outliers, I excluded those records from the dataset where StatedMonthlyIncome > 30K (around 0.2% of customers)

Although, it will be interesting to explore what factors can help predict default, considering the high default rate for Prosper, I am choosing to focus on APR hereonwards for bi-variate and multi-variate exploration

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.show();

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

I looked at how APR varies with other features in the dataset. The two fields that have a clear impact on the APR are ProsperScore and LoanOriginalAmount. There is a negative corrleation with both of them. As the Loan amount and Prosper score goes up, Borrower APR goes down. Employment status does seem to have an impact on APR as well, but I think it might already be factored in calculating the Prosper Score

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

There is a strong positive correlation between StatedMonthlyIncome and LoanOriginalAmount. Customers with high monthly income are able to take out higher loans, which makes sense

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The negative correlation between APR and Loan amount is further reinforced through the multivariate analysis, as the relationship holds for virtually all of the segments of data

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

For customers with ProsperScore 10 and 11, the APR is increasing with the loan amount, which seems counterintutive, based on the analysis we have seen so far. It may be due to size of this population (around 5.5% of the dataset), but worth investigating further
